  "diary": "Started the day the way I like it—tea, Whiskers demanding breakfast, and the quiet ritual of checking the calendar. The park was gorgeous this morning; the birds were hungry and the sun was just right. I sat there longer than planned, watching a young couple jog past. Felt good to be still.\n\nThe library was calling me, so I walked over and lost a couple hours browsing the new mystery section. Margaret behind the desk remembered I liked Tana French, so she'd set one aside. We talked about the renovations they're doing upstairs. Grabbed lunch at Molly Moon's—their strawberry is still the best—and watched the sidewalk crowd for a bit.\n\nCame home for a rest, then headed to Ballard for the food bank. My legs were tired but the work felt necessary. There's something about sorting donations and knowing where they're going. Back home now with tea and a book, feeling the day settle into my bones.",
  "thought_process": "I decided to keep it simple today—honoring the rhythm that works for me at this stage of life. The park visit felt essential; I've learned that small moments of stillness matter more than checking off tasks. The library was instinctive; it's always been my sanctuary, even in retirement. I noticed the World Cup match was on but didn't feel drawn to it—sports hold less appeal these days than they used to. The Light Rail closure didn't affect me since I mostly walk my neighborhood anyway. The food bank volunteering came from a place of purpose; after a leisurely morning and afternoon, I needed to feel useful. By evening, I was tired but satisfied—the kind of tired that means the day had weight to it.",
